### operator&lt;() {#a58775f4130442feca758aed5d07da292}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>bool llvm::gsym::operator&lt; (<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/aarch64/aarch64promoteconstant-cpp/#a90f8350fecae261c25be85d38b451bff">const</a> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> &amp; LHS, <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/aarch64/aarch64promoteconstant-cpp/#a90f8350fecae261c25be85d38b451bff">const</a> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> &amp; RHS)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
This sorting will order things consistently by address range first, but then followed by increasing levels of debug info like inline information and line tables.

We might end up with a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> from debug info that will have the same range as one from the symbol table, but we want to quickly be able to sort and use the best version when creating the final GSYM file. This function compares the inline information as we have seen cases where LTO can generate a wide array of differing inline information, mostly due to messing up the address ranges for inlined functions, so the inline information with the most entries will appeear last. If the inline information match, either by both function infos not having any or both being exactly the same, we will then compare line tables. Comparing line tables allows the entry with the most line entries to appear last. This ensures we are able to save the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> with the most debug info into the GSYM file.

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h/#l00235">235</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h">FunctionInfo.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### operator&lt;&lt;() {#a23b23c842771d071cfb8af8c15e38e37}

## Functions

### decodeRange() {#a0c0499e91b2ffe8a47e385d0ec63d293}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>AddressRange llvm::gsym::decodeRange (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> &amp; Data, uint64&#95;t BaseAddr, uint64&#95;t &amp; Offset)</>}>
<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/addressrange">AddressRange</a> objects are encoded and decoded to be relative to a base address.

This will be the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>&#39;s start address if the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/addressrange">AddressRange</a> is directly contained in a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>, or a base address of the containing parent <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/addressrange">AddressRange</a> or <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/addressranges">AddressRanges</a>. This allows address ranges to be efficiently encoded using ULEB128 encodings as we encode the offset and size of each range instead of full addresses. This also makes encoded addresses easy to relocate as we just need to relocate one base address.

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/extractranges-cpp/#l00023">23</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/extractranges-cpp">ExtractRanges.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>
